    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-11-06T18:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-11-06T18:10:00-05:00" n="110"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d110">
                <head>110. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d110fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 330/11–1359. Confidential; Priority. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_HVF1">Hartley</persName>; initialed by <persName
                            corresp="#p_CWI1">Cargo</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1"
                            >Sisco</persName>; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_NWT1"
                            >Nunley</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_LJM3">Ludlow</persName>;
                        and approved by <persName corresp="#p_WW6">Wallner</persName> who signed for
                        Herter.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1959-11-06T18:10:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 6, 1959—6:10 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_GADEL1">Gadel</gloss> 114. Re: <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                        >SC</gloss> Election. Dept agrees Polish intransigence re any compromise
                        (<gloss target="#t_DELGA1">Delga</gloss> 425<note n="2" xml:id="d110fn2">
                        <gloss target="#t_DELGA1">Delga</gloss> 425, November 13, reported that
                        Michalowski had informed Amadeo and Freitas-Valle that Poland was unwilling
                        to consider a compromise. (<hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>.)</note>) could offer
                    best hope gaining votes for Turkey. Moreover, Dept believes Polish attitude
                    underscores importance of at least maintaining unimpaired Turkish lead if our
                    bargaining position is not to be undermined. USGADel should continue therefore
                    stress as appropriate and in concert with Turks our hope countries in balloting
                    tomorrow will take into account Polish intransigence which may be aimed at
                    keeping seat vacant and thus providing basis for challenging legality future
                        <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> action which, as Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHCJ1">Lodge</persName> has pointed out, consistent with Soviet
                    “rule or ruin” approach.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
